# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: security-orchestration-soar
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Automation includes the use of various equipment and control systems such as machinery, processes in factories, boilers, and heat-treating ovens, switching on telephone networks, steering, stabilization of ships, aircraft and other applications and vehicles with reduced human intervention.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Examples range from a household thermostat controlling a boiler to a large industrial control system with tens of thousands of input measurements and output control signals.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] In the simplest type of an automatic control loop, a controller compares a measured value of a process with a desired set value and processes the resulting error signal to change some input to the process, in such a way that the process stays at its set point despite disturbances.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] This closed-loop control is an application of negative feedback to a system.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The mathematical basis of control theory began in the 18th century and advanced rapidly in the 20th.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The term *automation*, inspired by the earlier word *automatic* (coming from *automaton*), was not widely used before 1947, when Ford established an automation department.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] It was during this time that the industry was rapidly adopting feedback controllers, Technological advancements introduced in the 1930s revolutionized various industries significantly.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The World Bank's World Development Report of 2019 shows evidence that the new industries and jobs in the technology sector outweigh the economic effects of workers being displaced by automation.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Job losses and downward mobility blamed on automation have been cited as one of many factors in the resurgence of nationalist, protectionist and populist politics in the US, UK and France, among other countries since the 2010s.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] It was a preoccupation of the Greeks and Arabs (in the period between about 300 BC and about 1200 AD) to keep an accurate track of time.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] In Ptolemaic Egypt, about 270 BC, Ctesibius described a float regulator for a water clock, a device not unlike the ball and cock in a modern flush toilet.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] This was the earliest feedback-controlled mechanism.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The appearance of the mechanical clock in the 14th century made the water clock and its feedback control system obsolete.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The Persian Banū Mūsā brothers, in their *Book of Ingenious Devices* (850 AD), described a number of automatic controls.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Two-step level controls for fluids, a form of discontinuous variable structure controls, were developed by the Banu Musa brothers.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] They also described a feedback controller.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The design of feedback control systems up through the Industrial Revolution was by trial-and-error, together with a great deal of engineering intuition.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] It was not until the mid-19th century that the stability of feedback control systems was analyzed using mathematics, the formal language of automatic control theory.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The centrifugal governor was invented by Christiaan Huygens in the seventeenth century, and used to adjust the gap between millstones.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Another control mechanism was used to tent the sails of windmills.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Also in 1745, Jacques de Vaucanson invented the first automated loom.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Around 1800, Joseph Marie Jacquard created a punch-card system to program looms.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] In 1771 Richard Arkwright invented the first fully automated spinning mill driven by water power, known at the time as the water frame.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] An automatic flour mill was developed by Oliver Evans in 1785, making it the first completely automated industrial process.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Bunce of England in 1784 as part of a model steam crane.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The centrifugal governor was adopted by James Watt for use on a steam engine in 1788 after Watt's partner Boulton saw one at a flour mill Boulton & Watt were building.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The governor could not actually hold a set speed; the engine would assume a new constant speed in response to load changes.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The governor was able to handle smaller variations such as those caused by fluctuating heat load to the boiler.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Also, there was a tendency for oscillation whenever there was a speed change.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] As a consequence, engines equipped with this governor were not suitable for operations requiring constant speed, such as cotton spinning.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Several improvements to the governor, plus improvements to valve cut-off timing on the steam engine, made the engine suitable for most industrial uses before the end of the 19th century.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Advances in the steam engine stayed well ahead of science, both thermodynamics and control theory.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The governor received relatively little scientific attention until James Clerk Maxwell published a paper that established the beginning of a theoretical basis for understanding control theory.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Relay logic was introduced with factory electrification, which underwent rapid adaptation from 1900 through the 1920s.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Central electric power stations were also undergoing rapid growth and the operation of new high-pressure boilers, steam turbines and electrical substations created a great demand for instruments and controls.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Central control rooms became common in the 1920s, but as late as the early 1930s, most process controls were on-off.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Operators typically monitored charts drawn by recorders that plotted data from instruments.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] To make corrections, operators manually opened or closed valves or turned switches on or off.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Control rooms also used color-coded lights to send signals to workers in the plant to manually make certain changes.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The development of the electronic amplifier during the 1920s, which was important for long-distance telephony, required a higher signal-to-noise ratio, which was solved by negative feedback noise cancellation.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] This and other telephony applications contributed to the control theory.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] In the 1940s and 1950s, German mathematician Irmgard Flügge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic controls, which found military applications during the Second World War to fire control systems and aircraft navigation systems.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Controllers, which were able to make calculated changes in response to deviations from a set point rather than on-off control, began being introduced in the 1930s.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Controllers allowed manufacturing to continue showing productivity gains to offset the declining influence of factory electrification.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Factory productivity was greatly increased by electrification in the 1920s.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Alexander Field notes that spending on non-medical instruments increased significantly from 1929 to 1933 and remained strong thereafter.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The First and Second World Wars saw major advancements in the field of mass communication and signal processing.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Other key advances in automatic controls include differential equations, stability theory and system theory (1938), frequency domain analysis (1940), ship control (1950), and stochastic analysis (1941).
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] In 1959 Texaco's Port Arthur Refinery became the first chemical plant to use digital control.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Conversion of factories to digital control began to spread rapidly in the 1970s as the price of computer hardware fell.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The automatic telephone switchboard was introduced in 1892 along with dial telephones.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] By 1929, 31.9% of the Bell system was automatic.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Automatic telephone switching originally used vacuum tube amplifiers and electro-mechanical switches, which consumed a large amount of electricity.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Call volume eventually grew so fast that it was feared the telephone system would consume all electricity production, prompting Bell Labs to begin research on the transistor.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The logic performed by telephone switching relays was the inspiration for the digital computer.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The first commercially successful glass bottle-blowing machine was an automatic model introduced in 1905.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The machine, operated by a two-man crew working 12-hour shifts, could produce 17,280 bottles in 24 hours, compared to 2,880 bottles made by a crew of six men and boys working in a shop for a day.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The cost of making bottles by machine was 10 to 12 cents per gross compared to $1.80 per gross by the manual glassblowers and helpers.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Sectional electric drives were developed using control theory.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Sectional electric drives are used on different sections of a machine where a precise differential must be maintained between the sections.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] In steel rolling, the metal elongates as it passes through pairs of rollers, which must run at successively faster speeds.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] In paper making paper, the sheet shrinks as it passes around steam-heated drying arranged in groups, which must run at successively slower speeds.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The first application of a sectional electric drive was on a paper machine in 1919.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] One of the most important developments in the steel industry during the 20th century was continuous wide strip rolling, developed by Armco in 1928.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Before automation, many chemicals were made in batches.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] In 1930, with the widespread use of instruments and the emerging use of controllers, the founder of Dow Chemical Co. was advocating continuous production.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Self-acting machine tools that displaced hand dexterity so they could be operated by boys and unskilled laborers were developed by James Nasmyth in the 1840s.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Machine tools were automated with Numerical control (NC) using punched paper tape in the 1950s.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] This soon evolved into computerized numerical control (CNC).
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Today extensive automation is practiced in practically every type of manufacturing and assembly process.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Robots are especially useful in hazardous applications like automobile spray painting.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Robots are also used to assemble electronic circuit boards.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Automotive welding is done with robots and automatic welders are used in applications like pipelines.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] With the advent of the space age in 1957, controls design, particularly in the United States, turned away from the frequency-domain techniques of classical control theory and backed into the differential equation techniques of the late 19th century, which were couched in the time domain.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] During the 1940s and 1950s, German mathematician Irmgard Flugge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic control, which became widely used in hysteresis control systems such as navigation systems, fire-control systems, and electronics.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Through Flugge-Lotz and others, the modern era saw time-domain design for nonlinear systems (1961), navigation (1960), optimal control and estimation theory (1962), nonlinear control theory (1969), digital control and filtering theory (1974), and the personal computer (1983).
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Perhaps the most cited advantage of automation in industry is that it is associated with faster production and cheaper labor costs.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Another benefit could be that it replaces hard, physical, or monotonous work.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Additionally, tasks that take place in hazardous environments or that are otherwise beyond human capabilities can be done by machines, as machines can operate even under extreme temperatures or in atmospheres that are radioactive or toxic.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] They can also be maintained with simple quality checks.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] However, at the time being, not all tasks can be automated, and some tasks are more expensive to automate than others.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Initial costs of installing the machinery in factory settings are high, and failure to maintain a system could result in the loss of the product itself.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Automation primarily describes machines replacing human action, but it is also loosely associated with mechanization, machines replacing human labor.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The paradox of automation says that the more efficient the automated system, the more crucial the human contribution of the operators.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Humans are less involved, but their involvement becomes more critical.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Lisanne Bainbridge, a cognitive psychologist, identified these issues notably in her widely cited paper "Ironies of Automation." If an automated system has an error, it will multiply that error until it is fixed or shut down.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] A fatal example of this was Air France Flight 447, where a failure of automation put the pilots into a manual situation they were not prepared for.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Many roles for humans in industrial processes presently lie beyond the scope of automation.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Human-level pattern recognition, language comprehension, and language production ability are well beyond the capabilities of modern mechanical and computer systems (but see *Watson computer*).
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Tasks requiring subjective assessment or synthesis of complex sensory data, such as scents and sounds, as well as high-level tasks such as strategic planning, currently require human expertise.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] In many cases, the use of humans is more cost-effective than mechanical approaches even where the automation of industrial tasks is possible.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Therefore, algorithmic management as the digital rationalization of human labor instead of its substitution has emerged as an alternative technological strategy.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Overcoming these obstacles is a theorized path to post-scarcity economics.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] As of 2025-2026, real-world deployment of advanced robotics has revealed critical infrastructure limitations, such as "battery-life bottlenecks" (typically 2–4 hours of operation per charge) and the requirement for high-bandwidth Wi-Fi and specialized flooring for reliable function.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Additionally, robots continue to struggle with unpredictable human-made obstructions, which still necessitate human intervention to maintain operational flow.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Increased automation often causes workers to feel anxious about losing their jobs as technology renders their skills or experience unnecessary.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Early in the Industrial Revolution, when inventions like the steam engine were making some job categories expendable, workers forcefully resisted these changes.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Luddites, for instance, were English textile workers who protested the introduction of weaving machines by destroying them.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] More recently, some residents of Chandler, Arizona, have slashed tires and pelted rocks at a self-driving car, in protest over the cars' perceived threat to human safety and job prospects.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The relative anxiety about automation reflected in opinion polls seems to correlate closely with the strength of organized labor in that region or nation.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] According to one estimate, 47% of all current jobs in the US have the potential to be fully automated by 2033.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Furthermore, wages and educational attainment appear to be strongly negatively correlated with an occupation's risk of being automated.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Erik Brynjolfsson and Andrew McAfee argue that "there's never been a better time to be a worker with special skills or the right education, because these people can use technology to create and capture value.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Research by Carl Benedikt Frey and Michael Osborne of the Oxford Martin School argued that employees engaged in "tasks following well-defined procedures that can easily be performed by sophisticated algorithms" are at risk of displacement, and 47% of jobs in the US were at risk.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The study, released as a working paper in 2013 and published in 2017, predicted that automation would put low-paid physical occupations most at risk, by surveying a group of colleagues on their opinions.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] However, according to a study published in *McKinsey Quarterly* in 2015 the impact of computerization in most cases is not the replacement of employees but the automation of portions of the tasks they perform.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The methodology of the McKinsey study has been heavily criticized for being intransparent and relying on subjective assessments.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The methodology of Frey and Osborne has been subjected to criticism, as lacking evidence, historical awareness, or credible methodology.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Additionally, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) found that across the 21 OECD countries, 9% of jobs are automatable.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Based on a formula by Gilles Saint-Paul, an economist at Toulouse 1 University, the demand for unskilled human capital declines at a slower rate than the demand for skilled human capital increases.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] In the long run and for society as a whole it has led to cheaper products, lower average work hours, and new industries forming (i.e., robotics industries, computer industries, design industries).
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] These new industries provide many high salary skill-based jobs to the economy.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] By 2030, between 3 and 14 percent of the global workforce will be forced to switch job categories due to automation eliminating jobs in an entire sector.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] While the number of jobs lost to automation is often offset by jobs gained from technological advances, the same type of job loss is not the same one replaced and that leading to increasing unemployment in the lower-middle class.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] This occurs largely in the US and developed countries where technological advances contribute to higher demand for highly skilled labor but demand for middle-wage labor continues to fall.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Economists call this trend "income polarization" where unskilled labor wages are driven down and skilled labor is driven up and it is predicted to continue in developed economies.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Lights-out manufacturing is a production system with no human workers, to eliminate labor costs.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] It grew in popularity in the U.S. when General Motors in 1982 implemented humans "hands-off" manufacturing to "replace risk-averse bureaucracy with automation and robots".
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] However, the factory never reached full "lights out" status.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The costs of automation to the environment are different depending on the technology, product or engine automated.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] There are automated engines that consume more energy resources from the Earth in comparison with previous engines and vice versa.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Hazardous operations, such as oil refining, the manufacturing of industrial chemicals, and all forms of metal working, were always early contenders for automation.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The automation of vehicles could prove to have a substantial impact on the environment, although the nature of this impact could be beneficial or harmful depending on several factors.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Because automated vehicles are much less likely to get into accidents compared to human-driven vehicles, some precautions built into current models (such as anti-lock brakes or laminated glass) would not be required for self-driving versions.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Removal of these safety features reduces the weight of the vehicle, and coupled with more precise acceleration and braking, as well as fuel-efficient route mapping, can increase fuel economy and reduce emissions.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Despite this, some researchers theorize that an increase in the production of self-driving cars could lead to a boom in vehicle ownership and usage, which could potentially negate any environmental benefits of self-driving cars if they are used more frequently.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Automation of homes and home appliances is also thought to impact the environment.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] This study, along with others, indicated that the smart home's ability to monitor and adjust consumption levels would reduce unnecessary energy usage.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] However, some research suggests that smart homes might not be as efficient as non-automated homes.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] A more recent study has indicated that, while monitoring and adjusting consumption levels do decrease unnecessary energy use, this process requires monitoring systems that also consume an amount of energy.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The energy required to run these systems sometimes negates their benefits, resulting in little to no ecological benefit.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Another major shift in automation is the increased demand for flexibility and convertibility in manufacturing processes.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Manufacturers are increasingly demanding the ability to easily switch from manufacturing Product A to manufacturing Product B without having to completely rebuild the production lines.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Flexibility and distributed processes have led to the introduction of Automated Guided Vehicles with Natural Features Navigation.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Former analog-based instrumentation was replaced by digital equivalents which can be more accurate and flexible, and offer greater scope for more sophisticated configuration, parametrization, and operation.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] This was accompanied by the fieldbus revolution which provided a networked (i.e. a single cable) means of communicating between control systems and field-level instrumentation, eliminating hard-wiring.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Discrete manufacturing plants adopted these technologies fast.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The more conservative process industries with their longer plant life cycles have been slower to adopt and analog-based measurement and control still dominate.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The growing use of Industrial Ethernet on the factory floor is pushing these trends still further, enabling manufacturing plants to be integrated more tightly within the enterprise, via the internet if necessary.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Global competition has also increased demand for Reconfigurable Manufacturing Systems.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Engineers can now have numerical control over automated devices.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The result has been a rapidly expanding range of applications and human activities.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Computer-aided technologies (or CAx) now serve as the basis for mathematical and organizational tools used to create complex systems.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Notable examples of CAx include computer-aided design (CAD software) and computer-aided manufacturing (CAM software).
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The improved design, analysis, and manufacture of products enabled by CAx has been beneficial for industry.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Information technology, together with industrial machinery and processes, can assist in the design, implementation, and monitoring of control systems.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] One example of an industrial control system is a programmable logic controller (PLC).
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] PLCs are specialized hardened computers which are frequently used to synchronize the flow of inputs from (physical) sensors and events with the flow of outputs to actuators and events.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Human-machine interfaces (HMI) or computer human interfaces (CHI), formerly known as *man-machine interfaces*, are usually employed to communicate with PLCs and other computers.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Service personnel who monitor and control through HMIs can be called by different names.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] In the industrial process and manufacturing environments, they are called operators or something similar.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] In boiler houses and central utility departments, they are called *stationary engineers*.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Host simulation software (HSS) is a commonly used testing tool that is used to test the equipment software.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] HSS is used to test equipment performance concerning factory automation standards (timeouts, response time, processing time).
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Cognitive automation, as a subset of AI, is an emerging genus of automation enabled by cognitive computing.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Its primary concern is the automation of clerical tasks and workflows that consist of structuring unstructured data.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Cognitive automation relies on multiple disciplines: natural language processing, real-time computing, machine learning algorithms, big data analytics, and evidence-based learning.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Artificially intelligent computer-aided design (CAD) can use text-to-3D, image-to-3D, and video-to-3D to automate in 3D modeling.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] AI CAD libraries could also be developed using linked open data of schematics and diagrams.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Ai CAD assistants are used as tools to help streamline workflow.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Technologies like solar panels, wind turbines, and other renewable energy sources—together with smart grids, micro-grids, battery storage—can automate power production.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Many agricultural operations are automated with machinery and equipment to improve their diagnosis, decision-making and/or performing.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Agricultural automation can relieve the drudgery of agricultural work, improve the timeliness and precision of agricultural operations, raise productivity and resource-use efficiency, build resilience, and improve food quality and safety.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Increased productivity can free up labour, allowing agricultural households to spend more time elsewhere.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The technological evolution in agriculture has resulted in progressive shifts to digital equipment and robotics.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Motorized mechanization using engine power automates the performance of agricultural operations such as ploughing and milking.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] With digital automation technologies, it also becomes possible to automate diagnosis and decision-making of agricultural operations.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] For example, autonomous crop robots can harvest and seed crops, while drones can gather information to help automate input application.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Motorized mechanization has generally increased in recent years.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa is the only region where the adoption of motorized mechanization has stalled over the past decades.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Automation technologies are increasingly used for managing livestock, though evidence on adoption is lacking.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Adoption is likely mostly in Northern Europe, and likely almost absent in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Automated feeding machines for both cows and poultry also exist, but data and evidence regarding their adoption trends and drivers is likewise scarce.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Many supermarkets and even smaller stores are rapidly introducing self-checkout systems reducing the need for employing checkout workers.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] In the U.S., the retail industry employs 15.9 million people as of 2017 (around 1 in 9 Americans in the workforce).
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Globally, an estimated 192 million workers could be affected by automation according to research by Eurasia Group.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Online shopping could be considered a form of automated retail as the payment and checkout are through an automated online transaction processing system, with the share of online retail accounting jumping from 5.1% in 2011 to 8.3% in 2016.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] However, two-thirds of books, music, and films are now purchased online.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] In addition, automation and online shopping could reduce demands for shopping malls, and retail property, which in the United States is currently estimated to account for 31% of all commercial property or around 7 billion square feet (650 million square metres).
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Amazon has gained much of the growth in recent years for online shopping, accounting for half of the growth in online retail in 2016.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Other forms of automation can also be an integral part of online shopping, for example, the deployment of automated warehouse robotics such as that applied by Amazon using Kiva Systems.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The food retail industry has started to apply automation to the ordering process; McDonald's has introduced touch screen ordering and payment systems in many of its restaurants, reducing the need for as many cashier employees.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The University of Texas at Austin has introduced fully automated cafe retail locations.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Some cafes and restaurants have utilized mobile and tablet "apps" to make the ordering process more efficient by customers ordering and paying on their device.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Some restaurants have automated food delivery to tables of customers using a conveyor belt system.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The use of robots is sometimes employed to replace waiting staff.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Automation in construction is the combination of methods, processes, and systems that allow for greater machine autonomy in construction activities.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Construction automation may have multiple goals, including but not limited to, reducing jobsite injuries, decreasing activity completion times, and assisting with quality control and quality assurance.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Automated mining involves the removal of human labor from the mining process.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The mining industry is currently in the transition towards automation.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Currently, it can still require a large amount of human capital, particularly in the third world where labor costs are low so there is less incentive for increasing efficiency through automation.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) started the research and development of automated visual surveillance and monitoring (VSAM) program, between 1997 and 1999, and airborne video surveillance (AVS) programs, from 1998 to 2002.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Currently, there is a major effort underway in the vision community to develop a fully-automated tracking surveillance system.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Automated video surveillance monitors people and vehicles in real-time within a busy environment.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Existing automated surveillance systems are based on the environment they are primarily designed to observe, i.e., indoor, outdoor or airborne, the number of sensors that the automated system can handle and the mobility of sensors, i.e., stationary camera vs. mobile camera.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The purpose of a surveillance system is to record properties and trajectories of objects in a given area, generate warnings or notify the designated authorities in case of occurrence of particular events.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] As demands for safety and mobility have grown and technological possibilities have multiplied, interest in automation has grown.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Seeking to accelerate the development and introduction of fully automated vehicles and highways, the U.S.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Congress authorized more than $650 million over six years for intelligent transport systems (ITS) and demonstration projects in the 1991 *Intermodal Surface Transportation Efficiency Act* (ISTEA).
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Full automation commonly defined as requiring no control or very limited control by the driver; such automation would be accomplished through a combination of sensor, computer, and communications systems in vehicles and along the roadway.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Fully automated driving would, in theory, allow closer vehicle spacing and higher speeds, which could enhance traffic capacity in places where additional road building is physically impossible, politically unacceptable, or prohibitively expensive.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Automated controls also might enhance road safety by reducing the opportunity for driver error, which causes a large share of motor vehicle crashes.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Other potential benefits include improved air quality (as a result of more-efficient traffic flows), increased fuel economy, and spin-off technologies generated during research and development related to automated highway systems.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Automated waste collection trucks prevent the need for as many workers as well as easing the level of labor required to provide the service.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Business process automation (BPA) is the technology-enabled automation of complex business processes.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] It can help to streamline a business for simplicity, achieve digital transformation, increase service quality, improve service delivery or contain costs.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] BPA consists of integrating applications, restructuring labor resources and using software applications throughout the organization.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Robotic process automation (RPA; or RPAAI for self-guided RPA 2.0) is an emerging field within BPA and uses AI.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] BPAs can be implemented in a number of business areas including recruitment, marketing, sales and workflow.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Home automation (also called **domotics**) designates an emerging practice of increased automation of household appliances and features in residential dwellings, particularly through electronic means that allow for things impracticable, overly expensive or simply not possible in recent past decades.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The rise in the usage of home automation solutions has taken a turn reflecting the increased dependency of people on such automation solutions.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] However, the increased comfort that gets added through these automation solutions is remarkable.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Automation is essential for many scientific and clinical applications.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Therefore, automation has been extensively employed in laboratories.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] From as early as 1980 fully automated laboratories have already been working.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] However, automation has not become widespread in laboratories due to its high cost.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] This may change with the ability of integrating low-cost devices with standard laboratory equipment.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Autosamplers are common devices used in laboratory automation.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Logistics automation is the application of computer software or automated machinery to improve the efficiency of logistics operations.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Typically this refers to operations within a warehouse or distribution center, with broader tasks undertaken by supply chain engineering systems and enterprise resource planning systems.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Industrial automation deals primarily with the automation of manufacturing, quality control, and material handling processes.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] General-purpose controllers for industrial processes include programmable logic controllers, stand-alone I/O modules, and computers.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Industrial automation is to replace the human action and manual command-response activities with the use of mechanized equipment and logical programming commands.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] One trend is increased use of machine vision to provide automatic inspection and robot guidance functions, another is a continuing increase in the use of robots.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Industrial automation is simply required in industries.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The rise of industrial automation is directly tied to the "Fourth Industrial Revolution", which is better known now as Industry 4.0.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Originating from Germany, Industry 4.0 encompasses numerous devices, concepts, and machines, as well as the advancement of the industrial internet of things (IIoT).
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] An "Internet of Things is a seamless integration of diverse physical objects in the Internet through a virtual representation".
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] These new advancements have drawn attention to the world of automation and have shown ways for it to increase productivity and efficiency in machinery and manufacturing facilities.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Industry 4.0 works with the IIoT and software/hardware to connect in a way that (through communication technologies) add enhancements and improve manufacturing processes.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Being able to create more advanced manufacturing is now possible with these new technologies.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] It opens up an improved manufacturing platform.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Implementation of systems such as SCADA is an example of software that takes place in industrial automation today.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] SCADA is a supervisory data collection software, just one of the many used in industrial automation.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Industry 4.0 covers many areas in manufacturing.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Industrial robotics is a sub-branch in industrial automation that aids in various manufacturing processes.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Such manufacturing processes include machining, welding, painting, assembling and material handling to name a few.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Industrial robots use various mechanical, electrical as well as software systems to allow for high precision, accuracy and speed that far exceed any human performance.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The birth of industrial robots came shortly after World War II as the U.S. saw the need for a quicker way to produce industrial and consumer goods.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Servos, digital logic and solid-state electronics allowed engineers to build better and faster systems and over time these systems were improved and revised to the point where a single robot is capable of running 24 hours a day with little or no maintenance.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] In 1997, there were 700,000 industrial robots in use, the number has risen to 1.8M in 2017 In recent years, AI with robotics is also used in creating an automatic labeling solution, using robotic arms as the automatic label applicator, and AI for learning and detecting the products to be labelled.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Industrial automation incorporates programmable logic controllers in the manufacturing process.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) use a processing system which allows for variation of controls of inputs and outputs using simple programming.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] PLCs make use of programmable memory, storing instructions and functions like logic, sequencing, timing, counting, etc.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Using a logic-based language, a PLC can receive a variety of inputs and return a variety of logical outputs, the input devices being sensors and output devices being motors, valves, etc.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] PLCs are similar to computers, however, while computers are optimized for calculations, PLCs are optimized for control tasks and use in industrial environments.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] They are built so that only basic logic-based programming knowledge is needed and to handle vibrations, high temperatures, humidity, and noise.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The greatest advantage PLCs offer is their flexibility.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] With the same basic controllers, a PLC can operate a range of different control systems.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] PLCs make it unnecessary to rewire a system to change the control system.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] This flexibility leads to a cost-effective system for complex and varied control systems.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] PLCs can range from small "building brick" devices with tens of I/O in a housing integral with the processor, to large rack-mounted modular devices with a count of thousands of I/O, and which are often networked to other PLC and SCADA systems.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] They can be designed for multiple arrangements of digital and analog inputs and outputs (I/O), extended temperature ranges, immunity to electrical noise, and resistance to vibration and impact.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Programs to control machine operation are typically stored in battery-backed-up or non-volatile memory.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] It was from the automotive industry in the United States that the PLC was born.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Before the PLC, control, sequencing, and safety interlock logic for manufacturing automobiles was mainly composed of relays, cam timers, drum sequencers, and dedicated closed-loop controllers.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Since these could number in the hundreds or even thousands, the process for updating such facilities for the yearly model change-over was very time-consuming and expensive, as electricians needed to individually rewire the relays to change their operational characteristics.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] When digital computers became available, being general-purpose programmable devices, they were soon applied to control sequential and combinatorial logic in industrial processes.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] However, these early computers required specialist programmers and stringent operating environmental control for temperature, cleanliness, and power quality.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] To meet these challenges, the PLC was developed with several key attributes.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] It would tolerate the shop-floor environment, it would support discrete (bit-form) input and output in an easily extensible manner, it would not require years of training to use, and it would permit its operation to be monitored.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Since many industrial processes have timescales easily addressed by millisecond response times, modern (fast, small, reliable) electronics greatly facilitate building reliable controllers, and performance could be traded off for reliability.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Agent-assisted automation refers to automation used by call center agents to handle customer inquiries.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The key benefit of agent-assisted automation is compliance and error-proofing.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] Agents are sometimes not fully trained or they forget or ignore key steps in the process.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] The use of automation ensures that what is supposed to happen on the call actually does, every time.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p01] There are two basic types: desktop automation and automated voice solutions.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] Fundamentally, there are two types of control loop: *open-loop control* (feedforward), and *closed-loop control* (feedback).
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] One of the simplest types of control is *on-off* control.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] An example is a thermostat used on household appliances which either open or close an electrical contact.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] Sequence control, in which a programmed sequence of *discrete* operations is performed, often based on system logic that involves system states.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] An elevator control system is an example of sequence control.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] A proportional–integral–derivative controller (PID controller) is a control loop feedback mechanism (controller) widely used in industrial control systems.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] The theoretical understanding and application date from the 1920s, and they are implemented in nearly all analog control systems; originally in mechanical controllers, and then using discrete electronics and latterly in industrial process computers.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] Sequential control may be either to a fixed sequence or to a logical one that will perform different actions depending on various system states.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] An example of an adjustable but otherwise fixed sequence is a timer on a lawn sprinkler.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] States refer to the various conditions that can occur in a use or sequence scenario of the system.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] An example is an elevator, which uses logic based on the system state to perform certain actions in response to its state and operator input.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] For example, if the operator presses the floor n button, the system will respond depending on whether the elevator is stopped or moving, going up or down, or if the door is open or closed, and other conditions.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] Early development of sequential control was relay logic, by which electrical relays engage electrical contacts which either start or interrupt power to a device.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] Relays were first used in telegraph networks before being developed for controlling other devices, such as when starting and stopping industrial-sized electric motors or opening and closing solenoid valves.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] Using relays for control purposes allowed event-driven control, where actions could be triggered out of sequence, in response to external events.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] These were more flexible in their response than the rigid single-sequence cam timers.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] More complicated examples involved maintaining safe sequences for devices such as swing bridge controls, where a lock bolt needed to be disengaged before the bridge could be moved, and the lock bolt could not be released until the safety gates had already been closed.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] The total number of relays and cam timers can number into the hundreds or even thousands in some factories.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] Early programming techniques and languages were needed to make such systems manageable, one of the first being ladder logic, where diagrams of the interconnected relays resembled the rungs of a ladder.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] Special computers called programmable logic controllers were later designed to replace these collections of hardware with a single, more easily re-programmed unit.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] In a typical hard-wired motor start and stop circuit (called a *control circuit*) a motor is started by pushing a "Start" or "Run" button that activates a pair of electrical relays.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] The "lock-in" relay locks in contacts that keep the control circuit energized when the push-button is released.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] (The start button is a normally open contact and the stop button is a normally closed contact.) Another relay energizes a switch that powers the device that throws the motor starter switch (three sets of contacts for three-phase industrial power) in the main power circuit.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] Large motors use high voltage and experience high in-rush current, making speed important in making and breaking contact.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] This can be dangerous for personnel and property with manual switches.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] The "lock-in" contacts in the start circuit and the main power contacts for the motor are held engaged by their respective electromagnets until a "stop" or "off" button is pressed, which de-energizes the lock in relay.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] Commonly interlocks are added to a control circuit.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] Suppose that the motor in the example is powering machinery that has a critical need for lubrication.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] In this case, an interlock could be added to ensure that the oil pump is running before the motor starts.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] Timers, limit switches, and electric eyes are other common elements in control circuits.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] Solenoid valves are widely used on compressed air or hydraulic fluid for powering actuators on mechanical components.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] Computers can perform both sequential control and feedback control, and typically a single computer will do both in an industrial application.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) are a type of special-purpose microprocessor that replaced many hardware components such as timers and drum sequencers used in relay logic–type systems.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] General-purpose process control computers have increasingly replaced stand-alone controllers, with a single computer able to perform the operations of hundreds of controllers.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] Process control computers can process data from a network of PLCs, instruments, and controllers to implement typical (such as PID) control of many individual variables or, in some cases, to implement complex control algorithms using multiple inputs and mathematical manipulations.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] They can also analyze data and create real-time graphical displays for operators and run reports for operators, engineers, and management.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] Control of an automated teller machine (ATM) is an example of an interactive process in which a computer will perform a logic-derived response to a user selection based on information retrieved from a networked database.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] The ATM process has similarities with other online transaction processes.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] The different logical responses are called *scenarios*.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] Such processes are typically designed with the aid of use cases and flowcharts, which guide the writing of the software code.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/automation-p02] The earliest feedback control mechanism was the water clock invented by Greek engineer Ctesibius (285–222 BC).
[src:security-orchestration-soar/business-process-automation] With the increasing adoption of artificial intelligence (AI), organizations are implementing AI-driven technologies that can process natural language, interpret unstructured datasets, and interact with users.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/business-process-automation] These systems are designed to adapt to new types of problems with reduced reliance on human intervention.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/business-process-automation] A business process management system differs from BPA.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/business-process-automation] However, it is possible to implement automation based on a BPM implementation.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/business-process-automation] The methods to achieve this vary, from writing custom application code to using specialist BPA tools.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/business-process-automation] Robotic process automation (RPA) involves the deployment of attended or unattended software agents in an organization's environment.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/business-process-automation] These software agents, or robots, are programmed to perform predefined structured and repetitive sets of business tasks or processes.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/business-process-automation] Robotic process automation is designed to streamline workflows by delegating repetitive tasks to software agents, allowing human workers to focus on more complex and strategic activities.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/business-process-automation] BPA providers typically focus on different industry sectors, but the underlying approach is generally similar in that they aim to provide the shortest route to automation by interacting with the user interface rather than modifying the application code or database behind it.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/business-process-automation] Artificial intelligence software robots are used to handle unstructured data sets (like images, texts, audios) and are often deployed after implementing robotic process automation.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/business-process-automation] They can, for instance, generate an automatic transcript from a video.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/business-process-automation] The combination of automation and artificial intelligence (AI) enables autonomy for robots, along with the capability to perform cognitive tasks.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/business-process-automation] At this stage, robots can learn and improve processes by analyzing and adapting them.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] In computing, **managed security services** (**MSS**) are network security services that have been outsourced to a service provider.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] A company providing such a service is a **managed security service provider** (**MSSP**).
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] The roots of MSSPs are in the Internet service providers (ISPs) in the mid to late 1990s.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Initially, ISP(s) would sell customers a firewall appliance, as customer premises equipment (CPE), and for an additional fee would manage the customer-owned firewall over a dial-up connection.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] According to recent industry research, most organizations (74%) manage IT security in-house, but 82% of IT professionals said they have either already partnered with, or plan to partner with, a managed security service provider.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Businesses turn to managed security services providers to alleviate the pressures they face daily related to information security such as targeted malware, customer data theft, skills shortages and resource constraints.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Managed security services (MSS) are also considered the systematic approach to managing an organization's security needs.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] The services may be conducted in-house or outsourced to a service provider that oversees other companies' network and information system security.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Functions of a managed security service include round-the-clock monitoring and management of intrusion detection systems and firewalls, overseeing patch management and upgrades, performing security assessments and security audits, and responding to emergencies.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] There are products available from a number of vendors to help organize and guide the procedures involved.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] This diverts the burden of performing the chores manually, which can be considerable, away from administrators.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Newcomers to the market include a number of smaller providers used to protect homes, small businesses, and high networth clients.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] The IT partner intelligence source compuBase has identified more than 35,000 MSSPs worldwide (without Asia), and this number continues to grow as more VARs become MSPs and more MSPs offer Managed Security Services.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] An early example of an outsourced and off-site MSSP service is US West !NTERACT Internet Security.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] The security service didn't require the customer to purchase any equipment and no security equipment was installed at the customers premises.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] The service is considered an MSSP offering in that US West retained ownership of the firewall equipment and the firewalls were operated from their own Internet Point of Presence (PoP) The service was based on Check Point Firewall-1 equipment.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Following over a year long beta introduction period, the service was generally available by early 1997.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] The service also offered managed Virtual Private Networking (VPN) encryption security at launch.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] This is customized assistance in the assessment of business risks, key business requirements for security and the development of security policies and processes.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] It may include comprehensive security architecture assessments and design (include technology, business risks, technical risks and procedures).
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] This service involves installing, upgrading, and managing the firewall, Virtual Private Network (VPN) and/or intrusion detection hardware and software, electronic mail, and commonly performing configuration changes on behalf of the customer.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Management includes monitoring, maintaining the firewall's traffic routing rules, and generating regular traffic and management reports to the customer.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Intrusion detection management, either at the network level or at the individual host level, involves providing intrusion alerts to a customer, keeping up to date with new defenses against intrusion, and regularly reporting on intrusion attempts and activity.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Content filtering services may be provided by; such as, email filtering and other data traffic filtering.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Clearly not a managed service by itself, product resale is a major revenue generator for many MSS providers.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] This category provides value-added hardware and software for a variety of security-related tasks.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] One such service that may be provided is archival of customer data.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] This is the day-to-day monitoring and interpretation of important system events throughout the network—including unauthorized behavior, malicious hacks, denial of service (DoS), anomalies, and trend analysis.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] It is the first step in an incident response process.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] This includes one-time or periodic software scans or hacking attempts in order to find vulnerabilities in a technical and logical perimeter.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] It generally does not assess security throughout the network, nor does it accurately reflect personnel-related exposures due to disgruntled employees, social engineering, etc.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Regularly, reports are given to the client.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Conduct change management by monitoring event log to identify changes to a system that violates a formal security policy.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] For example, if an impersonator grants himself or herself too much administrative access to a system, it would be easily identifiable through compliance monitoring.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Unlike traditional MSS, which focuses on perimeter management and alert triage (sending notifications for the client to handle), managed detection and response focuses on rapid threat detection, analysis, investigation and response (the provider actually takes steps to contain the threat).
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] The decision criteria for engaging the services of an MSSP are much the same as those for any other form of outsourcing: cost-effectiveness compared to in-house solutions, focus upon core competencies, need for round-the-clock service, and ease of remaining up-to-date.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] An important factor, specific to MSS, is that outsourcing network security hands over critical control of the company's infrastructure to an outside party, the MSSP, whilst not relieving the ultimate responsibility for errors.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] The client of an MSSP still has the ultimate responsibility for its own security, and as such must be prepared to manage and monitor the MSSP, and hold it accountable for the services for which it is contracted.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] The relationship between MSSP and client is not a turnkey one.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Although the organization remains responsible for defending its network against information security and related business risks, working with an MSSP allows the organization to focus on its core activities while remaining protected against network vulnerabilities.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Business risks can result when information assets upon which the business depends are not securely configured and managed (resulting in asset compromise due to violations of confidentiality, availability, and integrity).
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Compliance with specific government-defined security requirements can be achieved by using managed security services.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] The business model behind managed security services is commonplace among large enterprise companies with their IT security experts.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] SMBs are increasingly turning to managed security services because they face a dangerous gap in coverage and capability.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] A primary driver is the "always-on" nature of modern threats; for instance, 91% of ransomware attacks occur outside regular business hours, a window during which most SMBs lack active monitoring.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] This vulnerability is compounded by internal resource gaps; SMBs perceive a lack of in-house expertise as their second biggest single cybersecurity risk, trailing only the threats themselves.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Of these organizations, many are constrained by budget limitations.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] To address the combined issues of lack of expertise, lack of time and limited financial resources, an emerging category of managed security service provider for the SMB has arisen.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Many organizations have begun adopting managed security services instead of relying solely on in-house IT security teams.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] In this model, companies outsource aspects of their information security operations to specialized service providers.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] This approach can allow organizations to reduce operational costs and focus on other business activities while maintaining continuous monitoring and management of their IT security systems.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] The growth of managed security services has been supported by the increasing involvement of major information technology companies and service providers.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Services providers in this category tend to offer comprehensive IT security services delivered on remotely managed appliances or devices that are simple to install and run for the most part in the background.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Fees are normally highly affordable to reflect financial constraints, and are charged every month at a flat rate to ensure predictability of costs.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Service providers deliver daily, weekly, monthly or exception-based reporting depending on the client's requirements.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Information technology security addresses threats such as cyberattacks malware, and email spoofing.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Managed Security Service Providers (MSSPs) offer services related to these security issues.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Vendors develop and maintain security solutions and service portfolios.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Global data protection regulations set requirements for data security.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Key sectors engaging managed security services include financial services, telecommunications, and information technology.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] MSS vendors develop and maintain technology offerings for client deployment.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Service models include cost management and integration of tools.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Service creation and product integration are part of these systems.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] The MSS market is present in regions including North America, Europe, Asia–Pacific, Latin America, the Middle East, and Africa.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Organizations increasingly engage managed security service providers (MSSPs) to meet regulatory requirements that demand continuous security monitoring and specialized expertise.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] The December 2024 HIPAA Security Rule NPRM proposed requiring continuous monitoring capabilities and 24-hour notification timelines for security incidents, requirements that many healthcare organizations rely on MSSPs to fulfill.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] Under HIPAA, MSSPs that access electronic protected health information are classified as business associates and must enter into business associate agreements with covered entities (45 CFR 164.308(b)).
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) version 4.0 requires daily review of security events and continuous monitoring of critical systems (Requirements 10.4 and 10.6), driving demand for managed security services among organizations processing payment card data.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/managed-security-service] NIST Special Publication 800-53 addresses outsourced security services through the SA-9 (External System Services) control, which requires organizations to ensure that external service providers comply with applicable security requirements.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/runbook] In a computer system or network, a **runbook** is a compilation of routine procedures and operations that the system administrator or operator carries out.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/runbook] System administrators in IT departments and NOCs use runbooks as a reference.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/runbook] Runbooks can be in either electronic or in physical book form.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/runbook] Typically, a runbook contains procedures to begin, stop, supervise, and debug the system.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/runbook] It may also describe procedures for handling special requests and contingencies.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/runbook] An effective runbook allows other operators, with prerequisite expertise, to effectively manage and troubleshoot a system.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/runbook] Through runbook automation, these processes can be carried out using software tools in a predetermined manner.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/runbook] In addition to automating IT specific processes, the results of the runbook can be presented on-screen back to the user or Service Desk engineer.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/runbook] Multiple runbooks can be linked together using a Decision Tree to provide users with interactive troubleshooting and guided procedures.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/runbook] Operational runbooks may be tied to ITIL incidents to allow repeatable processes supporting specific aspects of the service catalog.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/runbook] The runbook is typically divided into routine automated processes and routine manual processes.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/runbook] The runbook catalog begins with an index of processes covered and may be broken down in outline form to align the processes to the major elements they support in the service catalog.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/runbook] A runbook is a compilation of routine procedures and operations that the system administrator or operator carries out.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/runbook] The documentation for running a task, whether in electronic or paper form, is called a runbook.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/runbook] Sometimes written as "run book," it may supplement bullet-pointed steps with error messages (and what to do) and flowcharts.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/runbook] A runbook workflow can potentially interact with all types of infrastructure elements, such as applications, databases, and hardware - using a variety of communication methods such as command-line interfaces (CLI), HTTP REST and SOAP API's, SSH sessions, scripts, utilities, and code libraries.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/runbook] According to Gartner, the growth of RBA has coincided with the need for IT operations executives to enhance IT operations efficiency measures—including reducing mean time to repair (MTTR), increasing mean time between failures (MTBF), and automating the provisioning of IT resources.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/runbook] Patents have been granted for various aspects of producing, improving, and using runbooks.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/runbook] Some tools can incorporate a front-end or presentation layer (to the runbook) so that the results of the automated tasks are presented on-screen, sometimes even with red/amber/green traffic lights to visualise if a specific task completed successfully, or failed to execute correctly.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/runbook] More advanced runbook automation platforms incorporate dashboards, analytics and audit trails for regulatory reporting.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/security-orchestration] Organizations use SOAR platforms to improve the efficiency of physical and digital security operations.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/security-orchestration] SOAR enables administrators to handle security alerts without the need for manual intervention.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/security-orchestration] When a network tool detects a security event, SOAR can either alert the administrator or take another predefined action, depending on the event’s nature.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/security-orchestration] "Orchestration" connects the different security tools and systems of the Information system.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/security-orchestration] It integrates custom-built applications with built-in security tools, so they all work with each other.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/security-orchestration] It also connects diverse endpoints, firewalls and behavior analysis tools.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/security-orchestration] "Automation" takes the huge amount of information generated through orchestration and analyzes it through machine learning processes.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/security-orchestration] SOAR handles many manual tasks such as log analysis and can also handle ticket requests, vulnerability checks and auditing processes.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/security-orchestration] "Incident response" allows security teams to react when a potential threat is indicated.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/security-orchestration] This component also handles post-incident activities such as threat intelligence sharing in an automated way.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/security-orchestration] SOAR allows security administrators to define the potential incidents and the response, thanks to playbooks and runbooks.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/security-orchestration] A playbook is a document that describes how to verify a cybersecurity incident and how the incident should be responded.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/security-orchestration] The purpose of the playbook is to document what the runbook should do.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/security-orchestration] A playbook can also serve as a manual backup if the SOAR system fails.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/security-orchestration] A runbook implements the playbook data into an automated tool so that it performs predefined actions to mitigate the threat.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/workflow-engine] A **workflow engine** is a software application that manages business processes.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/workflow-engine] It is a key component in workflow technology and typically makes use of a database server.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/workflow-engine] A workflow engine manages and monitors the state of activities in a workflow, such as the processing and approval of a loan application form, and determines which new activity to transition to according to defined processes (workflows).
[src:security-orchestration-soar/workflow-engine] The actions may be anything from saving an application form in a document management system to sending a reminder e-mail to users or escalating overdue items to management.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/workflow-engine] A workflow engine facilitates the flow of information, tasks, and events.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/workflow-engine] Workflow engines may also be referred to as Workflow Orchestration Engines.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/workflow-engine] A workflow engine is a core technique for task allocation software, such as business process management, in which the workflow engine allocates tasks to different executors while communicating data among participants.
[src:security-orchestration-soar/workflow-engine] A workflow engine can execute any arbitrary sequence of steps, for example, a healthcare data analysis.
